{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528849"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:47:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:47:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14342"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14342"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.1,0.32,0.51,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7037"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58998"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7037"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14342"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44409"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1374"},{"type":"tags","id":"2451"},{"type":"tags","id":"4434"},{"type":"tags","id":"12805"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16744"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17526"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17530"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17703"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17724"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39970"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48370"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58998"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the hospital in active labour at 39 weeks gestation with her first child. She has no significant medical history and has had an uncomplicated pregnancy. She is receiving oxytocin augmentation. On examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a tense uterus with frequent contractions. The cardiotocograph (CTG) shows fetal deceleration lasting 4 minutes with a baseline heart rate of 80 beats per minute and reduced variability. The contraction pattern prior to bradycardia indicates uterine hyperstimulation with five contractions every 10 minutes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Start magnesium sulfate infusion","Apply fetal scalp electrode","Administer terbutaline","Perform immediate caesarean section","Continue oxytocin infusion"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario presents a case of fetal bradycardia with uterine hyperstimulation during labour, which requires immediate intervention to improve fetal oxygenation and prevent potential complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eadminister terbutaline\u003C/strong\u003E. Terbutaline is a beta-2 agonist that causes uterine relaxation, which can help resolve uterine hyperstimulation. By relaxing the uterus, it improves uteroplacental blood flow and fetal oxygenation, potentially resolving the fetal bradycardia. Terbutaline is typically given as a 250 microgram subcutaneous injection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuing oxytocin infusion\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate and potentially harmful in this situation. Oxytocin is likely contributing to the uterine hyperstimulation and should be discontinued immediately. Continuing it could worsen the fetal distress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eperforming an immediate caesarean section\u003C/strong\u003E might be necessary if the fetal deceleration does not resolve with conservative measures, it is not the most appropriate first step. Less invasive interventions should be attempted first, given the potential risks associated with emergency caesarean delivery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting magnesium sulfate infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this scenario. While magnesium sulfate has a role in preventing seizures in preeclampsia or for fetal neuroprotection in preterm labour, it is not the treatment of choice for uterine hyperstimulation or fetal bradycardia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApplying a fetal scalp electrode\u003C/strong\u003E might provide more accurate fetal heart rate monitoring, but it does not address the immediate problem of hyperstimulation and fetal bradycardia. It would not be the priority in this emergency situation if the current abdominal CTG tracing is considered adequate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to administering terbutaline, other important steps in managing this situation include discontinuing the oxytocin infusion, repositioning the mother (usually to the left lateral position to improve uteroplacental blood flow), and administering oxygen. If these measures do not promptly resolve the fetal bradycardia, preparation for emergency caesarean section should be initiated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fetal deceleration with uterine hyperstimulation in labour requires prompt intervention to improve fetal oxygenation.","Terbutaline is a beta-2 agonist that can be used to relax the uterus and resolve hyperstimulation in labour.","Repositioning the mother, discontinuing oxytocin, and administering oxygen are important initial steps in managing fetal distress during labour."],"references":["Laurence KM, Chan R, Hong J, Pepperell A. The fetal bradycardia. O\u0026G Magazine [Internet]. 2017 [cited 2024 Oct 9];19(2). Available from: https://www.ogmagazine.org.au/19/2-19/the-fetal-bradycardia/","Chandraharan E, Arulkumaran S, Tourn\u00e9 L, Singhal N. Optimizing the management of acute, prolonged decelerations and fetal bradycardia based on the understanding of fetal pathophysiology. Am J Obstet Gynecol. 2023;228(6):645-56."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44409"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14342"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44409"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-04T08:28:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-04T08:29:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7037"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58998"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Le